As I was writing my 
hashtag
#newbook on 
hashtag
#datastorytelling, I had an interesting epiphanyâ€”data storytellers are change agents. Whenever we discover a new insight, the natural consequence of that insight is change. Stop doing that, and do more of this. Focus less on them, and concentrate more on these people. Spend less there, and invest more over here.

In our excitement to share our insights, we forget we're inviting change. There will always be resistance to changeâ€”even if itâ€™s for the better. Author Dan Millman said, â€œThe secret of change is to focus all of your energy, not on fighting the old, but on building the new.â€ Rather than trying to destroy the pre-existing narrative in our audienceâ€™s minds that may be based on outdated, incomplete, or erroneous data, we need to build a new narrative with our new insights. If youâ€™ve read my book already, you know I place a lot of emphasis on driving action with insights. Data storytellers need to anticipate the resistance their insights will encounter. If we can craft our data stories more effectively, we can help mitigate and overcome this resistance to change.

Mixture experiments are a special class of response surface experiments in which the product under investigation is made up of several components or ingredients. Designs for these experiments are useful because many product design and development activities in industrial situations involve formulations or mixtures. In these situations, the response is a function of the proportions of the different ingredients in the mixture. For example, you might be developing an insecticide that blends four chemical ingredients.

Knowledge or mere being aware has blurred the lines between a good and average leadership. 
This diagram depicts  differences  between Tacit Knowledge and Explicit Knowledge but also  between two kinds of Tacit Knowledge: Know Why and Know How. Tacit Know Why deals with values, feelings, motives, relationships and significance. Tacit Know How deals with intuitive interaction, habit, muscle-memory and competence. By contrast, Explicit Know What deals with facts, categories, models and metrics. Some might prefer to differentiate facts and metrics from categories and models. A problem arises when we conflate any of these three (or four) ways of knowing, imposing either 1. values, 2. skills, 3. data, or 4. categories as an exclusive or dominating epistemology. Why would we do this? It seems that psychological temperament,  social conditioning, educational experience and existential choice each play a role in deciding which of these ways of knowing we trust the most and assume to be regulative of the others. Even here there are those who will tend to pick only one or two of these four factors as the regulative and decisive ones, ignoring or minimizing the other factors that â€œjust donâ€™t agree with themâ€

"Itâ€™s important to remember the proliferation of the edge is a result of demand, not a strategic choice of network owners." - Angie McMillan

Sometimes, we look at the way the world is shaping up, and there's a tendency to think that corporations and businesses are defining the ways in which we live, work, and play. But the moves of business are made to meet the demands of...everyone else. Consumers want more data more quickly at a higher quality, and they want it now. Mission critical enterprises NEED the same.

Edge computing is moving more rapidly today than expected. That movement, that growth, is driven by want and by need. The edge will be from now forward supporting what may be a permanent shift towards an even more computer-driven society. 

It's occuring to me today that all of the predictions for the edge, the way it will shape and how fast it will do so, may very well go out the window this year. What we knew yesterday we have no knowledge of today. We no longer know the future of data and of edge computing. We know there will be increased need and demand, and that's it. 

What do you think is next for edge computing now?

Logistic Regression 
It's classification problem algorithm , it's supervised learning problem we have numaric data , yes or no type values yes for 1 and no means 0 , so it's binary classification problem .

In logistic Regression we use probability to predict correct classification of data items , it's optimization technic .

It's two class problem so we devide training data into two class and set hyperplan between the classes to saperate data items and class . Then we use sigmoid function which is calculate the probability and by that sigmoid value we can predict the testing data is belong to class A or class B . 

If sigmoid value is .5 then testing data on the hyperplan which shows that the testing data is belong to both classes.

If testing data value is greater than .5 then it's belong to class A .

And if testing data value is smaller then .5 then it's belong to class B .

So we optimize correctly and predict yes and no type problems by Logistic Regression correctly .
